SKILL|ascii-video|"ASCII video: convert video/audio to colored ASCII MP4/GIF."
STEP|1|Before writing a single line of code**, articulate the creative concept. What is the mood? What visual story does this tell? What makes THIS project different from every other ASCII video? The user's 
STEP|2|First-render excellence is non-negotiable.** The output must be visually striking without requiring revision rounds. If something looks generic, flat, or like "AI-generated ASCII art," it is wrong — r
STEP|3|Go beyond the reference vocabulary.** The effect catalogs, shader presets, and palette libraries in the references are a starting vocabulary. For every project, combine, modify, and invent new pattern
STEP|4|Be proactively creative.** Extend the skill's vocabulary when the project calls for it. If the references don't have what the vision demands, build it. Include at least one visual moment the user didn
STEP|5|Cohesive aesthetic over technical correctness.** All scenes in a video must feel connected by a unifying visual language — shared color temperature, related character palettes, consistent motion vocab
STEP|6|Dense, layered, considered.** Every frame should reward viewing. Never flat black backgrounds. Always multi-grid composition. Always per-scene variation. Always intentional color.
STEP|7|**INPUT** — Load/decode source material (video frames, audio samples, images, or nothing)
STEP|8|**ANALYZE** — Extract per-frame features (audio bands, video luminance/edges, motion vectors)
STEP|9|**SCENE_FN** — Scene function renders to pixel canvas (`uint8 H,W,3`). Composes multiple character grids via `_render_vf()` + pixel blend modes. See `references/composition.md`
STEP|10|**TONEMAP** — Percentile-based adaptive brightness normalization. See `references/composition.md` § Adaptive Tonemap
STEP|11|**SHADE** — Post-processing via `ShaderChain` + `FeedbackBuffer`. See `references/shaders.md`
STEP|12|**ENCODE** — Pipe raw RGB frames to ffmpeg for H.264/GIF encoding
STEP|13|**Different background effect** (or compose 2-3)
STEP|14|**Different character palette** (match the mood)
STEP|15|**Different color strategy** (or at minimum a different hue)
STEP|16|**Vary shader intensity** (more bloom during peaks, more grain during quiet)
STEP|17|**Different particle types** if particles are active
STEP|18|A custom character palette matching the theme
STEP|19|A custom background effect (combine/modify existing building blocks)
STEP|20|A custom color palette (discrete RGB set matching the brand/mood)
STEP|21|A custom particle character set
STEP|22|A novel scene transition or visual moment
STEP|23|**Mood/atmosphere**: What should the viewer feel? Energetic, meditative, chaotic, elegant, ominous?
STEP|24|**Visual story**: What happens over the duration? Build tension? Transform? Dissolve?
STEP|25|**Color world**: Warm/cool? Monochrome? Neon? Earth tones? What's the dominant hue?
STEP|26|**Character texture**: Dense data? Sparse stars? Organic dots? Geometric blocks?
STEP|27|**What makes THIS different**: What's the one thing that makes this project unique?
STEP|28|**Emotional arc**: How do scenes progress? Open with energy, build to climax, resolve?
STEP|29|**Mode** — which of the 6 modes above
STEP|30|**Resolution** — landscape 1920x1080 (default), portrait 1080x1920, square 1080x1080 @ 24fps
STEP|31|**Hardware detection** — auto-detect cores/RAM, set quality profile. See `references/optimization.md`
STEP|32|**Sections** — map timestamps to scene functions, each with its own effect/palette/color/shader config
STEP|33|**Output format** — MP4 (default), GIF (640x360 @ 15fps), PNG sequence
STEP|34|**Hardware detection + quality profile** — `references/optimization.md`
STEP|35|**Input loader** — mode-dependent; `references/inputs.md`
STEP|36|**Feature analyzer** — audio FFT, video luminance, or synthetic
STEP|37|**Grid + renderer** — multi-density grids with bitmap cache; `references/architecture.md`
STEP|38|**Character palettes** — multiple per project; `references/architecture.md` § Palettes
STEP|39|**Color system** — HSV + discrete RGB + harmony generation; `references/architecture.md` § Color
STEP|40|**Scene functions** — each returns `canvas (uint8 H,W,3)`; `references/scenes.md`
STEP|41|**Tonemap** — adaptive brightness normalization; `references/composition.md`
STEP|42|**Shader pipeline** — `ShaderChain` + `FeedbackBuffer`; `references/shaders.md`
STEP|43|**Scene table + dispatcher** — time → scene function + config; `references/scenes.md`
STEP|44|**Parallel encoder** — N-worker clip rendering with ffmpeg pipes
STEP|45|**Main** — orchestrate full pipeline
STEP|46|**Test frames first**: render single frames at key timestamps before full render
STEP|47|**Brightness check**: `canvas.mean() > 8` for all ASCII content. If dark, lower gamma
STEP|48|**Visual coherence**: do all scenes feel like they belong to the same video?
STEP|49|**Creative vision check**: does the output match the concept from Step 1? If it looks generic, go back
STEP|50|**Forced Connections** — when the user wants cross-domain inspiration ("make it look organic," "industrial aesthetic")
STEP|51|**Conceptual Blending** — when the user names two things to combine ("ocean meets music," "space + calligraphy")
STEP|52|**Oblique Strategies** — when the user is maximally open ("surprise me," "something I've never seen")
STEP|53|Pick a domain unrelated to the visual goal (weather systems, microbiology, architecture, fluid dynamics, textile weaving)
STEP|54|List its core visual/structural elements (erosion → gradual reveal; mitosis → splitting duplication; weaving → interlocking patterns)
STEP|55|Map those elements onto ASCII characters and animation patterns
STEP|56|Synthesize — what does "erosion" or "crystallization" look like in a character grid?
STEP|57|Name two distinct visual/conceptual spaces (e.g., ocean waves + sheet music)
STEP|58|Map correspondences (crests = high notes, troughs = rests, foam = staccato)
STEP|59|Blend selectively — keep the most interesting mappings, discard forced ones
STEP|60|Develop emergent properties that exist only in the blend
STEP|61|Draw one: "Honor thy error as a hidden intention" / "Use an old idea" / "What would your closest friend do?" / "Emphasize the flaws" / "Turn it upside down" / "Only a part, not the whole" / "Reverse"
STEP|62|Interpret the directive against the current ASCII animation challenge
STEP|63|Apply the lateral insight to the visual design before writing code
